Instagram Update: All The Latest Changes Right Now

August 15, 2019 in Guides

There’s a good reason why Instagram changes all of the time.

Now that the channel has more than 1 billion monthly active users to satisfy, it can afford to fall behind the curve. Instagram wants to be your go-to channel for authentic, attractive, and engaging content – particularly when you’re on your smartphone.

If the platform wants to stay ahead of competitors like Facebook and Twitter, then it needs to roll out the occasional update. However, we’ve seen a massive selection of changes to Instagram over the last few months, ranging from new creator profiles to enhanced Stories features, and new ban policies.

Perhaps the biggest Instagram update for 2019 isn’t what the channel is adding- it’s what it’s removing. Instagram is officially testing the option to remove like counts from your feed.

Say what?

Read on to learn more about the biggest Instagram updates for the end of 2019.

Instagram Update 1: A New Camera for Instagram Stories

Instagram Stories has more than 500 million active users.

It’s no big surprise then that one of the main focuses of the F8 conference for 2019 was the Stories feature. One of the most recent additions to the tool is a new camera mode and an update to the standard camera functionality.

The standard Camera mode allows users to swipe to the right to access all their favourite shooting options like Superzoom, Rewind, and Boomerang. If you swipe to the left, you’ll find all the creative tools on Instagram Stories, like stickers, text, GIFs, and more.

The alternative Create Mode available from Instagram Stories allows users to create content without uploading a video or photo first. This is perfect for anyone who wants to create a quick text-based story or poll with their followers.Â 

Instagram Update 2: Creator Profiles

Another major update for the second half of 2019 was the introduction of a new profile for Instagram users. This “Creator” profile claims to support influencers rather than traditional businesses. Though the Creator profile is similar to the Business account in many ways, with access to things like Instagram Insights and contact buttons, it also comes with a few extra benefits.

For instance, as a Creator, you’ll have access to a Studio that delivers in-depth analytics about engagement, when your audience gets online, and what kind of demographics you reach best. You’ll also see your follow/unfollow data, and unlock a wider range of DM filtering options, so you can reduce the number of annoying messages you get each day.

At first, Creator profiles sound fantastic – but there are some downsides. For instance, you won’t be connected to the Instagram API as a Creator. That means that you can’t schedule automatic posts for Instagram or use any third-party tools for your analytics.Â 

Additionally, rumors indicate that these new profiles will only be available to influencers on Instagram with a specific follower count.

Instagram Update 3: New Stories Stickers

Is it just us, or does it seem like new Instagram updates always include at least some kind of sticker? Throughout 2019, we’ve seen the arrival of new shoppable stickers, advanced poll stickers, and even donation stickers for charities. The feel-good donation sticker from Instagram is perfect for non-profits who want to create new fund-raising opportunities directly from their Instagram profile. Anyone who clicks on the sticker can enter a donation on Instagram and send money straight to the causes that they care about.

At the time of writing, the donation sticker is only available in the US, but Instagram will be rolling the functionality out further afield too. Instagram also rolled out the chat sticker this year too. This provides another way for brands to interact with their customers. Essentially, users add the chat sticker to their Story, which invites followers to use a new group-chat based around that story. When users click on the sticker, they can request to join the conversation.

The IG team introduced this Instagram update as a way to get people talking about things that they have in common. However, there’s always the option for brands to use the tool to connect with influencers or a small segmented audience.

One issue is that the sticker is a bit difficult to use. If you have a broad audience and you use the chat sticker, you might get swamped by requests if you’re not careful.

Instagram Update 4: Stories Stores Content for Longer

Speaking of the most recent Instagram changes to the Stories section, Instagram also announced that they will be increasing the amount of time that users have to access the content in their Stories section. Usually, when you took a video or captured a picture in Stories mode, Instagram would only store the material for 24 hours – even if you didn’t publish it.

However, now, Instagram has announced that you’ll be able to access everything you capture in the Stories app for 7 days.

Obviously, this new Instagram update is helpful for any company that wants to make sure that they can make the most out of their Stories or re-use any critical content they’ve captured. It might just be a tiny tweak – but it’s a big deal if you shoot content native in Story mode.

You can even use this feature to create Instagram content for Stories in advance and post it throughout the remainder of the week.

Instagram Update 5: Anyone Can Create a Filter

The Spark AR studio from Facebook and Instagram has been the topic of conversation for a while now in the Instagram space. However, it was only after the F8 conference for 2019 that this feature became even more impressive. Facebook revealed this year that anyone can now create their very own Instagram Stories filter using the Spark studio.

Until now, the feature had only been available for brands and designers working in collaboration with Instagram. However, Mac and PC users will be able to log into the feature going forward. This means that even smaller companies can create AR experiences for their audience.

The decision to open Spark AR up to more developers and platform is a big one for Facebook and the Instagram team. We expect to see more businesses and brands getting creative with their custom AR effects going forward. You might have already noticed companies like Kylie Cosmetics experimenting with filters that allow users to test lipsticks before they buy them.

Instagram Update 6: Ad Placements in the Explore Section

Instagram recently announced the decision to place ads in the Explore section of the social media platform. This means that when users are scrolling through the Explore section of their app, they’ll be able to click on a post and scroll through a feed of posts that have been compiled by Instagram to suit their interests. The feed will have been created by the Instagram algorithm, based on previous content that the user has clicked on.

Usually, users take advantage of the Explore section to help them discover new accounts and brands that they want to connect with. However, Instagram is now introducing a new way to implement ads into the Explore experience too. For brands, this is excellent news, as it means that you’ll have more ways to reach your target audience and gain impressions.

Ads in the Explore page will appear just like a normal Instagram post so that they won’t jolt your audience out of their browsing experience. This feature is set to roll out slowly over the remainder of 2019. However, IGTV already has ads up and running in its Explore segment.

Instagram Update 7: Like Removal is on the Horizon

Now we come to perhaps the biggest Instagram update that we’ve seen so far – the decision to remove likes from the Instagram feed.

When the rumour about likes being stripped from Instagram first emerged on the market, Instagram didn’t say much about it at all. Recently, however (June), the company announced that the test is being rolled out across 6 regions, including Brazil, Australia, Ireland, Canada, New Zealand, and Japan.

Crucially, Instagram likes will still be a part of the platform, even if they’re removed from your news feed. What’s more, they’re still going to be a component in how Instagram decides how to rank crucial content. As usual, the more likes and comments will always count towards your chances of ranking on the Explore page.

So why deliver an Instagram update that removes likes?

Instagram says it’s because they want people to focus on the quality of the photos and videos you share, rather than just connecting with content that other people like. The social channel wants to remove some of the focus on Likes that could create a bit of a group mentality among your audience.

Instagram Update 8: Better Ways to Banish Bullying

During the F8 conference for 2019, Facebook also announced that its team was looking into new features that would help to combat bullying on the platform. According to Adam Mosseri, there’s a good chance that some features will never come to light. However, others are more likely. For instance, one option may be to introduce an “Away Mode” that allows users to opt-out of Instagram when they’re having a difficult time emotionally.

If you’d just suffered from a tough break up, and you didn’t want to interact with your friends on Instagram during that time, the Away Mode would give you a break without asking you to delete your account or app.

Another of the potential Instagram changes coming in the future to target bullying is a “nudge” feature. This will present a small message to a user who might be planning on posting something negative on a friend’s content. The feature won’t censor any content. However, it will give users a chance to think twice about what they’re going to say.

Instagram Update 9: Updated Ban Policies

Instagram recently made some changes to their account disabling policies designed to improve the experience that all users get with the channel. According to the latest updates, the changes will warn individuals when they might be able to get themselves into hot water.

Today, Instagram disables any account that posts too much content violating their community guidelines. However, troublesome accounts can sometimes get around these rules, which is frustrating for the rest of us. Moving into 2020, there will be a policy in place to allow Instagram to shutdown accounts that make several violations within a specific period. This enables Instagram to be more vigilant with their policies.

Additionally, to make sure that you have a chance to change your ways, Instagram will also be introducing a feature to let you know that you’re “toeing the line” of getting into trouble.Â  The warnings explain what a community violation involves, and what you’ve done wrong recently, so you know how to keep yourself out of trouble in the future.

This is part of an over-arching change to the Facebook and Instagram terms of service that have been growing more significant across the last year. Overall, the companies want to make using Instagram feel as safe as possible for everyone.

Keeping Up with the Instagram Updates

2019 has been a massive year for Instagram so far.

Since reaching the 1 billion user mark in 2018, the channel has been devoting more time and focus than ever before into creating a truly unique experience for its target audience.

Probably the biggest news of all is the idea that we may not have any likes on Instagram feed anymore. Combined with the arrival of ads in the Instagram Explore page, and changes to the Instagram Stories camera mode, it’s safe to say that there are going to be a lot of big differences to the way that you use your favorite social media channel.

Stay tuned to SocialFollow to make sure that you’re always up to date with the latest Instagram changes to appear in the industry.
